es' criticisms. In Graham's view, Parmenides plays a constructive role in shaping the scientific debates of the fifth century BC. Accordingly, the history of Presocratic philosophy can be seen not as a series of dialectical failures, but rather as a series of theoretical advances that led to empirical discoveries. Indeed, the Ionian tradition can be seen as the origin of the scientific conception of the world that we still hold today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh  aAbsolute (philosophy).  aAlcmaeon of Croton.  aAlexander of Aphrodisias.  aAllusion.  aAmbiguity.  aAnalogy.  aAnaxagoras.  aAnaximander.  aAnaximenes.  aAntidosis.  aApeiron (cosmology).  aAristotle.  aAtomism.  aCausality.  aChemical element.  aChemical formula.  aClassical element.  aCoeus.  aConcept.  aContradiction.  aCosmogony.  aCratylus.  aCrius.  aCronus.  aDemocritus.  aDiogenes of Apollonia.  aDualism (philosophy of mind).  aDualism.  aEleatics.  aEmergence.  aEmpedocles.  aEmpirical evidence.  aEssence.  aExistence.  aExplanandum.  aExplanation.  aExplication.  aFallacy.  aFirst principle.  aFour causes.  aGreek Philosophy.  aHippias.  aHypothesis.  aIgnoratio elenchi.  aInference.  aInquiry.  aInstance (computer science).  aIsocrates.  aLeucippus.  aLucretius.  aMaterial monism.  aMeteorology.  aMonism.  aMultitude.  aMythology.  aNatural philosophy.  aNatural science.  aOn Generation and Corruption.  aOn the Heavens.  aOntology.  aOusia.  aParmenides.  aPeripatetic school.  aPhenomenon.  aPhilolaus.  aPhilosopher.  aPhilosophical theory.  aPhilosophy.  aPre-Socratic philosophy.  aPremise.  aPrinciple.  aProcess philosophy.  aProse.  aP